eventName: Walk 100km with your dog in November for Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Throughout November and the beginning of December, Bayley, Roscoe and I (Jamie and Mila may get involved from one walk to another!) will be walking 100km (hopefully more!) to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support.

This challenge is really important to me for many reasons. Like many of you, I have lost loved ones to cancer. I lost my dear Nan to cancer nearly ten years ago and I miss her dreadfully. And only two months ago I lost a dear, old friend of mine, James, who will always hold a special place in my heart. Everyone who gets cancer deserves life-transforming support and so with my loved ones in mind, I’m doing whatever I can to help Macmillan be there for anyone with cancer.

Any donation amount will be greatly appreciated. I’ll share updates of a muddy and wet Bayley and Roscoe (and myself probably!) and the walks as we complete the challenge. Thank you! 🐶🐾💚

P.s. Just for you James I will be putting the earbuds in and listening to Savage Garden, Bon Jovi and Greenday 🥰

Below is some information about Macmillan Cancer Support. 

There’s around 3 million people living with cancer in the UK today, and over 360,000 more are diagnosed every year. Right now, millions of people with cancer are counting on Macmillan for physical, financial and emotional support.

At Macmillan, they do whatever it takes – last year was no exception. But they can't do it alone. Macmillan is facing a huge drop in income as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. Because 97% of their work is funded by people like us, they need our support now more than ever. Visit their website to find out more https://www.macmillan.org.uk/. 💚

story:
My team have been through a lot this year. A Ministerial office feels like the heart of the storm, with no headspace to focus on your personal life. But sometimes the personal doesn’t wait for things to stop spinning.

For ‘Movember’, I’m fundraising for Macmillan Cancer Support. A phenomenal organisation, and a cause our team has special reason to rally behind. 

I’ve never been able to grow much of a beard, so I’m giving up coffee for a month. Full disclosure, I am a massive caffeine addict. The average 'designer coffee' from Starbucks, Costa or Café Nero costs approximately £3. I humbly ask that you consider forgoing just one coffee this month, and visit my JustGiving page to contribute the cost instead to help people with cancer and their loved ones weather the storm. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity to provide an efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

Wish me luck! ☕️

story:
Garib Dass sadly passed away on Saturday 30th October 2021 at the age of 78, after a brief battle with lung cancer.

Garib was born on the 9th October 1943 to Lachman Dass and Nami in Manguwal, India. He migrated to England at the young age of 17 to work as a laborer, providing support for his family back home. He was one of five brothers who he loved immensely: late Tarsem and Naranjan, surviving brothers Piara and Gurnam. In 1964 Garib married Charan Kaur, and together they had 5 children: Rajinder, Surendra, Sarbjit, Balvinder and Harbans. 

He was an enthusiastic, family-oriented man who loved socializing. Garib always made time for everyone he knew, and lived a colorful life.  

In lieu of flowers people wishing to honor Garib's lifelong commitment to his family, can make donations to the Macmillan Cancer Support Charity - of which we are extremely grateful for.

His tireless love and devotion to his family were evident in his final moments.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
eventName: Walk 100km with your dog in November
story:
I know this may not be the toughest of challenges, I walk Olive everyday. But charities have never needed our help as much as they do now, with many events last year having been cancelled due to Covid. And let’s face it who hasn’t been touched by cancer in some way!

We lost a very special friend to cancer, Tan, at a very young age. She inspired me to run The London Marathon for Breast Cancer. That was seven years ago, so I thought it was about time I did something else.

Macmillan is quite often the first point of contact for a  family going through cancer. Without our help, they can’t help and provide the much needed support.

So I’m joining in to help raise awareness of this amazing charity and hopefully raise a little bit of money on the way. Every little helps right 👊🏻

Thank you for your support, you’re wonderful 💚

eventName: Walk 100Km with your dog in November
story: Poppy and I are walking 100km this November for Macmillan and your contribution will make an impact, whether you donate £5 or £500. Every little bit helps. Thank you for your support. Below is some information about Macmillan Cancer Support. There’s around 3 million people living with cancer in the UK today, and over 360,000 more are diagnosed every year. Right now, millions of people with cancer are counting on Macmillan for physical, financial and emotional support. At Macmillan, they do whatever it takes – last year was no exception. But they can't do it alone. Macmillan is facing a huge drop in income as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. Because 97% of their work is funded by people like us, they need our support now more than ever. Visit their website to find out more https://www.macmillan.org.uk/.

A group of us; myself, Jacob, Thomas, Nils, Lukas, and Tom are undertaking Movember this year to raise money to fight cancer. We would greatly appreciate any donation large or small to help us reach our goal.

We'll be posting regular updates of our beautiful faces as the month progresses to see who can cultivate the best moustache.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
eventName: Walk 100km with your dog in November
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.Want to join me in supporting a good cause?

 I'm walking 100km with my dogs this November for Macmillan and your contribution will make an impact, whether you donate £5 or £500. Every little bit helps. Thank you for your support. Below is some information about Macmillan Cancer Support.
There’s around 3 million people living with cancer in the UK today, and over 360,000 more are diagnosed every year. Right now, millions of people with cancer are counting on Macmillan for physical, financial and emotional support.
At Macmillan, they do whatever it takes – last year was no exception. But they can't do it alone. Macmillan is facing a huge drop in income as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. Because 97% of their work is funded by people like us, they need our support now more than ever. Visit their website to find out more https://www.macmillan.org.uk

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thanks for supporting our fundraising event. 

We are taking part in a Stepathon in order to raise funds for Macmillan Cancer Support. This will be done in our own time but together as a team. Our goal is to achieve 100k steps within the week and to push ourselves that little bit more physically in order to achieve this, just like those at Macmillan do everyday. 

If you have ever been effected by cancer or a loved one has, then please support this fund raising event by donating anything at all in order to help us achieve our target and to give back to those who are there to help us when we are in need.

Thank you in advance for your support & donations.

eventName: Mike and Em’s Virtual  Mt Kilimanjaro challenge
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. I wanted to do something a little different to raise some money for a great cause that helped me when I was going through the hardest time . 

Last year I had a life changing operation due to having cancer.  As a consequence I’m not the fittest any more and with my dodgy leg this will be a big challenge for me, so I’ve asked Emma to be my wingman!  The challenge is for us to walk a virtual route up Mt Kilimanjaro of 97km over 5 weeks!  

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

story:
The Great Septuple Challenge

1. Sheffield Half Marathon 13.1 Miles Sunday -27th of March

2. Leeds Half Marathon 13.1 Miles Sunday - 8th of May

3. Peak Challenge - 50 km Saturday and Sunday - 9th - 10th July

4. Dronfield 10K Monday - 29th of August

5. Peak District Challenge 50 km. Saturday - 17th of September

6. Sheffield 10 km September - Sunday - 25th of September

7. Yorkshire Marathon 26 miles Sunday - 16th of October

I lost my dad to lung cancer two years ago and a friend to skin cancer. The Macmillian was there for my dad and my friend. I want to raise as much money that is possible for the Macmillan Cancer Support. This challenge will also honour my father and my friend.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. charity.description:
At Macmillan, we will move mountains to help people with cancer live life as fully as they can.

We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us. To
donate, volunteer, raise money or campaign with us, call 0300 1000 200 or visit macmillan.org.uk
charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
CBRE are proud to partner Macmillan Cancer Support.

Living with cancer can be devastating at the best of times, but even harder as a result of the recent pandemic.  At Macmillan, we talk to people affected by cancer every day and for many, issues with money and mental health such as stress and depression, are their biggest worry.

Our partnership focuses on tackling financial hardship and loneliness together, helping Macmillan develop their telephone, online and virtual support services and to help thousands more people with much needed financial and emotional support.

The CBRE partnership is going to be more important than ever before, to help Macmillan do whatever it takes to support every single person living with cancer.

Cancer is not going anywhere.  And neither can Macmillan.

Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.

charity.description:
At Macmillan, we will move mountains to help people with cancer live life as fully as they can.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thank you for supporting the Boyle family fundraising. We have set a modest target for this event and we are confident that our great friends will do all they can to help us exceed those expectations.  

It has been the bleakest of times for so many people over the last couple of years and we thought that we could spread a little positivity whilst doing what we do best and having the best of good times.  

Macmillan will be needed more than ever by those who have not had the access to care levels that were available pre-covid.  A cancer diagnosis is a shattering experience, life changing and earth shaking.  Macmillan nurses act as the stabilisers through those rocky waters and we would like to show our unending gratitude to them.  Their work does not stop at supporting the patient, the whole family benefit from their strength and wisdom. Their work is essential. 

The work that Macmillan do, we are in awe of, and we hope that you will dig deep in your pockets and help us spread a little comfort.  Then please bring yourselves along, enjoy a glass of mulled wine and a VERY warm welcome back to our home before dusting off your dancing boots and seeing if we still know how to do it!  

Let's Party!!!!!!

story:

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising.  Cancer seems to touch nearly everyone in some way. It has impacted many people in my life including my friends, family and colleagues.  Over 10 years ago, I lost my amazing mother in law who lost her fight for cancer in such a short space of time.

I wanted to join my 19 year old son, Lucas Patel who has been training intensively for a Charity Boxing Match at the end of November.  I enjoy running and through the years always wanted to accomplish the goal of running at least a half marathon.  Injuries, surgery and life in general set me back over the years, then Covid-19 hit.  I thought I would not be able to run again following a lower back surgery 5 years ago, I was determined to get back on my feet and give it my best shot.

I will be running the Victoria Park Half Marathon on Saturday 6th November 2021.  It’s a huge event for me and many others I’m sure.  However, the challenge I face is no where near what many people go through with loved ones and battling with Cancer.

A little note of encouragement would go a long way to getting across the finishing line and any small donations are hugely appreciated – thank you in advance.

Let’s beat cancer together!!  Let’s do this!!  Let’s support each other!! 

xxx

Thanks for supporting my fundraising.  I was diagnosed with Neuroendocrine Tumour with primary on my pancreas and “in excess of 20 tumours” on my liver in 2010. I underwent operations to remove half my pancreas, my spleen, three liver resections and my gall bladder was removed. Still it came back. I then had 4 treatments of Lutetium, which cured the NET but has since caused myeloma diagnosed in 2017 after presenting with 2 compression fractures in my spine.  For that I have had back to back stem cell transplants which lasted less than a year and have been on a series of chemo treatments since, which, although not pleasant, have kept me  alive 😊. 

100 km (60 miles) in a month walking the dogs may not seem too hard to achieve, but for someone who struggles climbing the stairs some days it is a bit of a challenge. Any support you can give to this charity and my challenge would be very much appreciated. Thank you.

story:
I am raffling of a SiobhansCrafts DK advent calendar rrp - £65 + post

I am doing this in memory of a wonderful customer of mine who sadly passed away from cancer before she could enjoy her advent calendar. It is her families wishes that find the calendar a new home, so i thought i would set up a raffle to raise some funds in her memory.

Every £1 donated will be one entry in raffle - (e.g if you donate £5 your name will go into the pot 5 times)

**When you donate please leave your instagram name or email so i can contact you if you are the winner. **

On Monday 8th November 2021 i will draw the winner live via instagram live (@SiobhansCrafts) any donations made after i have drawn the winner will not be valid for the draw. I will post the advent calendar to the winner anywhere in the world at my own personal cost.

Information on the prize:

The theme this year for our advent calendar is "butterflies" 🦋.

What's going to be inside this advent calendar?

1 x exclusive project bag to keep all your minis in.
1 x exclusive enamel pin
24 x micro (10g each) hand dyed skeins based upon the theme "butterflies" in a actual advent box, with doors and numbers!! This means you will have 240 grams of dk hand dyed yarn in total . There will also be lots of surprises in the box too!!

I am pouring my heart and soul into these calendars to make sure you're not disappointed. 🥰

The yarns whether you choose sock or dk will by a 75% sw merino/ 25% nylon blend.
Dk = 22m per 10g mini

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
We are raising money for Macmillan Cancer in memory of our beloved Yousif Lathram. We lost Yousif to lung cancer back in November 2019. We would like to raise money for this charity in Yousif's name to help other families through this difficult journey. So we shall be walking the South Downs Half Marathon on the 12th of June, 2022 as Team Lush! (he would have agreed with and been very amused by this name :) )

Yousif was a smart man with a zest for life; he loved to dance, drink, laugh, and be silly. He was also generous and kind to everyone he met and loved all his family. Even though he had a difficult journey he maintained a brave stance until the very end for the sake of us all.

Macmillan offers emotional, physical, and financial support to families affected by cancer and we think it's one of the best cancer charities out there. Any donation you can make, no matter how small, will help to support families that are going through the same experience.

Thank you for supporting us and Macmillan Cancer Support.

With much love and thanks,

Valerie (wife), Olivia (daughter) & Miral (daughter in law)

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Around 6 years ago I was diagnosed with testicular cancer.   I was extraordinarily luck, that it is very treatable and I was diagnosed exceptionally early.

Earlier this year I was given the all-clear after 5 years of follow-up.  For that I am truly grateful. 

Movember is normally about prostate cancer awareness so I feel like I'm hijacking it a bit.  But this is personal, and as Macmillan were fantastically supportive I'd like to support them.  I, fortunately, hardly needed their services, except for reassurance in the early days, but I've witnessed many people including my own father 40 years ago, who needed Macmillan 's support to the very end.

I've set a very modest goal.  Please support me with a couple of pounds.

Thank you

charity.description:
The nation’s leading first aid charity.
Every year, more than 400,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes.
Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
eventName: St John Ambulance – Rushall All Services Unit Fundraising
story:
As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future.

This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. 

St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve.  

During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country.

"I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." 
Tom Willis, volunteer 

Will you support me and help make a difference?

charity.description:
The nation’s leading first aid charity.

Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
St John Ambulance empower communities to step forward in the moments that matter to save lives.  
Every year, more than 800,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes, including hundreds of thousands of young people. 

Our ambulances are a familiar sight at public events and our volunteers give many hours of their own time to provide first aid in their communities, keeping people safe at events, and working alongside the NHS in response to 999 calls. 
The importance of St John Ambulance cannot be overestimated. It can quite literally make the difference between a life lost and a life saved.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: We will be growing Mustaches over November for The British Heart Foundation. I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Every day, 250 people in the UK start to lose their sight. When someone loses their sight, were here to make sure they dont lose their freedom as well.
 
Every penny you raise a part of #TeamGuideDogs will go towards helping us provide life-changing services for people with sight loss.

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
eventName: Moray Volunteer Fundraising Group 12 Dogs of Christmas Fundraiser
story:
This Christmas,  help me give a life-changing gift to someone with sight loss.

Together we could fund 12 new guide dog partnerships. Each guide dog could give someone with sight loss the gift of confidence to get out and about safely. 
Whether helping their owner visit family or friends, or to shop for that special surprise gift for a loved one. Your fundraising will help provide life-changing practical support not just at Christmas, but all year round.

From enjoying every magical Christmas moment, to the simple festive pleasures that most people take for granted. Our ambition is a future where everyone with sight loss is able to live the life they choose.

Thank you.

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page. On the 3rd April 2022 we will be running the London Landmarks Half Marathon for Guide Dogs. This will be Sarah's first half marathon and we will be training throughout the winter months. 

Guide Dogs is the world’s largest breeder and trainer of guide dogs for the visually impaired. Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives.

Guide Dogs provide more than just training of puppies, they also offer services and support to help those living with sight loss. Breeding and training a guide dog comes at a huge financial cost and the demand for guide dogs is ever increasing.

We are hoping to raise as much money as possible for this cause so any small amount can help. Thanks in advance!

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Great Ormond Street has been a part of our lives for many different reasons. 

My cousin Jess was treated there for many years as she fought Neuroblastoma. She fought this for 7 years and sadly we had to say goodbye to her in 2018 at the tender age of 10. She was so bubbly and always had a permanent smile on her face and she always thought of others before herself.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
I am aiming to cycle 300 miles in 30 days to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children’s Charity. To put that into perspective - I will be riding the distance from Brighton to Blackpool!

This charity has always been close to my heart and I would like to raise awareness of the hard work and dedication that GOSH have to saving the lives of babies and children.

Monies raised will be used for the following:

- rebuilding and refurbishment of wards and medical facilities designed around children, helping the hospital treat more patients

- ground breaking research to find treatments for the most complex childhood illnesses

- advanced medical equipment for treating the toughest and rarest conditions 

- child and family support services that can ease the burden on families, raise spirits, and support children and young people through their treatment.

For anyone who knows me…this is a huge challenge. Just one gym class usually has me floored - so have fun watching me unable to walk for the entire month of November!  

Due to the cold weather, I will be making up my miles by a mix of indoor cycling on the weekdays (including spin classes), and outdoor cycling on the weekends. My aim is to complete 10 miles a day, however as a working mother, time is of the essence! So it’s likely I’ll be taking some days off in the week and be forced to double my miles on the other days. Overall, I promise I won’t make it easy on myself!  All cycles will be tracked and logged onto MapMyRun, and added onto my page below.

Wish me luck - and please donate..every £ and p counts to saving another life.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

20 years ago I gave birth to our amazing son Zack. He was so eager to begin his life that he rocked up a couple of weeks early, and very very quickly! You can imagine how happy and excited we all were.

However, it became apparent very soon after his birth that something was not right. When trying to feed him he didn't seem to be able to take my milk down and he was going blue and finding it difficult to breathe. 

After we raised the alarm 3 or 4 times, a few hours after his birth he was taken to the hospital's intensive care unit to be assessed and monitored. The consultant diagnosed that he had a rare condition that affect's the babies oesophagus ( food pipe) and trachea ( windpipe) called TOF/OA ( Tracheo-Oesophageal Fistula and an Oesohageal Artresia).

Basically his oesophagus from his mouth didn't reach his stomach so he couldn't swallow anything. And the part of his oesophagus that was attached to his stomach was attached to his trachea, so acid, air and fluid in his stomach was going into his lungs so he couldn't breathe properly.

He required urgent surgery to correct these abnormalities. 

We were so blessed that we lived in London and Great Ormond Street Hospital was on our doorstep so he was rushed late that night by ambulance to this truly wonderful place. Very early the following morning he underwent major surgery. Our tiny newborn baby had a 4 hour operation to join his oesophagus together and close up the resultant hole in his trachea.

We thought that everything was 'fixed' and that he would be fine. However, at 2.00am the following morning we received an urgent call from the ICU advising that the procedure had to be redone as there had been complications. His lungs collapsed and he was extremely poorly.

The staff at GOSH were unbelievably amazing. They helped both Kenny and I to cope with an absolutely terrifying situation, providing a safe and reassuring environment for us both when we were both completely lost. They saved Zack's life on more than one occasion and continued caring for him regularly, both when he had to be readmitted due to illness and through regular out patient appointments to monitor his development right up to the age of 10.

Kenny and I cannot thank GOSH enough for saving Zack's life. I want to raise as much money as I can for the staff and hospital, so that they can help as many children and their families as possible. I'm therefore running the London Landmark's 1/2 marathon next April with my sister Sal for the GOSH charity.

I would really appreciate any donation that you can give to support the phenomenal GOSH staff and all the  hospital's initiatives. As an example of how your money will help, we were put up in a room round the corner from the hospital for the days that Zack was in ICU so that we could be with him. This was funded through charity donations. The money also goes towards research, life saving equipment, building and refurbishment and supporting all the families and children that are dealing with extremely frightening and life threatening conditions.

A HUGE THANK YOU to you all for your kindness and generosity.

Much love 

Julia X

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Hello! Thank you for visiting my JustGiving page.

I'm so proud to say that I've been selected to be a part of Team GOSH for the London Marathon in October 2022 to help raise money for the hospital and a cause very close to my heart.

You may or may not know that this isn't actually my first time being part of Team GOSH. I was a patient at the hospital for just over 15 years from around the ages of 3-18. The hospital is a truly unique place and has undoubtedly played a big role in shaping the person I am today.

Mine is just one story of gratitude, but it's certainly not one that is individual to me. Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive at Great Ormond Street Hospital. Every day, doctors and nurses battle some of the most complex illnesses and work together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. Despite the complexities and seriousness of all the work going on, what really makes GOSH unique and something that has always stuck with me is that time for fun, laughter and creating a space for kids to be kids is never lost sight of. Smiles are infectious and  every visit to the hospital was an overwhelmingly positive experience despite the often painful and uncomfortable treatments which I was there for.

One thing you will definitely know about me is that I'm not a runner. A mixture of genuine concern to straight out laughter has been the general reaction to me telling my friends I was thinking of doing the marathon with a special mention to "You are the last person I would think of to be doing a marathon" from the big DC.

This is going to be a real challenge for me, however one that I couldn't think of a better cause to do it for. Ever since leaving GOSH 7 years ago, I have always wanted to do something to say thank you for the care, support and experience I received at Great Ormond Street and to help support it to give the same to thousands of other children every year. Being selected for Team GOSH has enabled me to go a small way in doing this. The hospital has always depended on charitable support and so I know that the money raised here and by everyone in Team GOSH for the 2022 Marathon will help to support GOSH to give seriously ill children the chance of a better future.

Thank you so much for reading this message, for your generosity and for your support (I'll definitely need it!)

Love

Tom x

For more information about the work GOSH does and to find out where Team GOSH's fundraising will go visit the website: https://www.gosh.org/what-we-do

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
We've been caring for people with serious illnesses in Barnet, Brent, Camden, Enfield, Haringey and Islington for more than 60 years, now.

Every single day at the hospice is an extraordinary day. And every moment is precious. Our hospice nurses, doctors and therapists provide the best possible care for people with serious illnesses, and offer vital emotional support for them and their families. 

The hospice is a warm, welcoming place where loved ones can be together in peaceful surroundings and in as much comfort as possible. Whether it's for one day or several weeks, the time people spend at the hospice is precious, and is cherished by them and their families.

Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in North London get the care and support they need.

"When I was admitted, I was confined to a wheelchair, in constant pain. Now I walk between five and seven miles a day. You can see how good Marie Curie is in that I walk" - Matthew

story:
When Georgina told me before her wedding that after she would be cutting her beautiful long hair to donate to the little princess trust, I felt impelled to support her and do the same. This year was the 15th anniversary of my dearly loved and sorely missed mother who lost her life to that horrid illness CANCER!

So it seemed very fitting to double up the charity fund raising. As you can see in the photo my hair is now very long. I estimate that if I cut very short like I last had my hair 21 years ago, I could donate 16 inches. This is a big step for me to take. Not being able to grab a hairband to tie back my hair will feel very strange. 

My hair cut is all booked for 10th December. The minimum donation is 7 inches, I am asking for donations to give me encouragement to give more. I will donate an extra inch for every £50 raised up to the maximum 16 inches I have. 😉 

The little princess trust makes real hair wigs for little girls that have lost their beautiful hair because of the nasty treatments they are having to try and fight cancer. Just think how happy it would make a little girl receiving a nice long hair wig rather than a shorter one. 

By donating you will be helping to charities that support cancer patients in very different ways. I have chosen Marie Curie as they were very supportive to my mother and family during our time of need. 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
As some of you may already know, I am absolutely mad about everything to do with the RNLI and I can't wait to be 17 so that I can become a volunteer, only 10 years to go !

For my birthday this year, I have requested that instead of birthday presents, any money that you would have spent on a gift for me, to be donated to the RNLI instead, either via this link or in my birthday card which I will forward onto the RNLI. 

In support of my request, the RNLI have generously donated items to be included within the party bags as a thank you for your support.

I hope to raise a reasonable sum towards my favourite charity and thank you in advance for your donations and look forward to seeing you at my party.

Thank you

Jack 

RNLI Storm Force Member

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place. Thank you.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
To quote Lt Cdr USN Smith, Sea King Pilot on the night of 19th December 1981:

"Throughout the entire rescue evolution the Penlee Crew never seemed to hesitate. After each time they were washed, blown or bumped away from the casualty the Penlee  immediately started another run in. Their spirit and dedication was amazing considering the horrific hurricane seas and the constant pounding they were taking. The greatest act of courage that I have ever seen, and am likely to ever see, was the penultimate courage and dedication shown by the Penlee when it manoeuvred back alongside the casualty in over 60 foot breakers and rescuing four people shortly after the Penlee had been bashed on top of the casualty's hatch covers.

They were truly the bravest eight men I've ever seen who were also totally dedicated to upholding the highest standards of the RNLI."

That terrible night is now 40 years ago and those men should be remembered for at least another generation, and the community that nurtured such heroes celebrated for its heart and spirit.

Thanks for Rannoch Adventure of Burnham on Couch for providing the organisation for the expedition.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
About RNLI
We are taking on an English Channel relay in June 2022 to raise money for RNLI, whose volunteer lifeboat crews do vital work saving lives at sea.
Their humanitarian work in the English Channel to rescue vulnerable people attempting to cross the Channel in small boats was in particular focus in 2021, and they have been forced to defend themselves against xenophobic rhetoric from some politicians. As RNLI CEO Mark Dowie puts it; "when it comes to rescuing those people attempting to cross the Channel, we do not question why they got into trouble, who they are or where they come from. All we need to know is that they need our help."
RNLI lifeguards also keep watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands, and the RNLI safety teams and educators work tirelessly to educate and inform people on water safety. 
We are hoping to raise £2,000 to help them keep up the important work they do. 

About the team
We are a group of four amateur masters swimmers (Daniel Mills, Kal Jhugroo, Thomas Mills and Chris Knight) based at Trafford Metro BSC and Open Swim in Manchester. All of us competed at elite junior level and have carried on swimming through our 20s and 30s. Between us we hold British Junior and Masters swimming records, and have competed at international level in the pool and open water.  
We are hoping to complete the 21 mile (33km) swim in around 8 hours, which would be a new 4-person relay World Record. For it to be recognised as official swim we need to complete it in only short swim trunks, goggles and non-thermal swim caps. The water temperature in early June is likely to be around 12-14 degrees - brrr!

We will be sharing our journey including training sessions and cold water swimming tips over the coming months!
Thanks for your support.
TT x

This year I've decided to set myself an ambitious goal. I'll be taking part in the Everest Base Camp Trek in aid of WWF. I'll be undertaking this challenging 11-day trek through the Nepal Himalaya to reach the iconic Everest Base Camp at 5,645m!

My challenge will support WWF, who are the world's leading independent conservation organisation with the mission to create a world where people and wildlife can thrive together. I'm supporting WWF because we are the first generation that knows we are destroying the world and the last that can do anything about it. Our planet is suffering but together we can make a difference and fight for our world.  

That is why any donation big or small, sharing my fundraising page, or even just spreading awareness of WWF is hugely appreciated! 

Thank you for all your support.

story:
Hi my name is Finn, and I'm joining WWF to Wear it Wild and get FIERCE for our world!

I live near Richmond Park and I love all the wildlife that live there. I'm 9years old and I recently learnt a lot about climate change and how litter can harm our world and the wildlife who live in it. I decided to help WWF, so every weekend, me, my family and my friends are going to dress up as animals, go out walking and pick up litter! Here's a message from WWF-UK..

Wear it wild. Help Finn raise funds to protect and take action for our planet. We want to see you wear any animal-inspired clothing. Brave it, Rock it, Nail it, Boss it, Strut it. Because if we are going to protect our world, we need to be fiercer, braver and louder than we've ever been. So, from the playground to the workplace, no matter how you Wear it Wild, join Finn and get fierce for your world!

charity.description:

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
This year I've decided to set myself an ambitious goal. I'll be taking part in the Everest Base Camp Trek in aid of WWF. I'll be undertaking this challenging 11-day trek through the Nepal Himalaya to reach the iconic Everest Base Camp at 5,645m!

My challenge will support WWF, who are the world's leading independent conservation organisation with the mission to create a world where people and wildlife can thrive together. I'm supporting WWF because we are the first generation that knows we are destroying the world and the last that can do anything about it. Our planet is suffering but together we can make a difference and fight for our world.  

That is why any donation big or small, sharing my fundraising page, or even just spreading awareness of WWF is hugely appreciated! 

Thank you for all your support. 

If you'd like to find out any more information or join the fight for our world please visit https://www.wwf.org.uk/

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Min Ji is a little girl who lives in London. She enjoys going to school, chasing her friends in circles, burnt toast at breakfast clubs, going on holidays and all the regular things that children do. When Covid-19 shut the schools down, like all other Year 2 children, she discovered the joy of solitude and her friendship with her soft toys transcended to a whole new level. With all the time in the world to herself, she started writing about her toy chicken going on an adventure around the world, based loosely on her pre-Covid holidays and the places that she may one day visit when the pandemic is over. I hope you enjoy the book. If you do, please feel free to make an optional donation of any amount which will go to UNICEF.
